In C, you don't have high-level abstractions like `[::-1]`. You have to manipulate memory directly. Use two pointers. One at the start, one at the end. Swap and converge.
```c
void reverse(char *str) {
    if (!str) return;
    char *end = str + strlen(str) - 1;
    while (str < end) {
        char temp = *str;
        *str++ = *end;
        *end-- = temp;
    }
}
```
Make sure your string is mutable. If you try this on a string literal, you'll get a Segfault. Don't say I didn't warn you.

The Singleton pattern... often an anti-pattern if overused. But if you must: make the constructor private. Create a static instance. 
```java
public class Singleton {
    private static final Singleton INSTANCE = new Singleton();
    private Singleton() {}
    public static Singleton getInstance() { return INSTANCE; }
}
```
There are thread-safe lazy-loading versions too, but start with the basics.

Pass by pointer. 
```c
void swap(int *a, int *b) {
    int temp = *a;
    *a = *b;
    *b = temp;
}
```
If you just pass `int a, int b`, you are swapping local copies on the stack, and the caller sees no change.

Iterative is safer, recursive is cleaner. 
```python
def factorial(n):
    return 1 if n == 0 else n * factorial(n-1)
```
Or just `import math; math.factorial(n)`. Why reinvent the wheel?

It involves a sequence of Hadamard gates and controlled phase rotations $R_k$. 
```python
def qft(qubits):
    for i in range(len(qubits)):
        yield cirq.H(qubits[i])
        for j in range(i + 1, len(qubits)):
            yield cirq.CZ(qubits[j], qubits[i])**(1 / 2**(j - i))
```
Note the phase power. It gets very small very fast. Precision matters.
